<subfield code="a">1 online resource (157 p.)</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1="1" ind2=" " tag="490"><subfield code="a">Routledge Critical Studies in Buddhism</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="504"><subfield code="a">Includes bibliographical references and index.</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1="0" ind2=" " tag="505"><subfield code="a">The King's daughter -- What is a woman? -- A woman's traditional path : from daughter to wife -- Only Dhamma pays off the filial debt -- Motherhood as a soteriological path -- Bhikkhun&#299;s and the four assemblies -- The Buddhist family.</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="506"><subfield code="a">Access restricted to authorized users and institutions.</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="520"><subfield code="a">The P&#257;li tradition presents a diverse and often contradictory picture of women. This book examines women's roles as they are described in the P&#257;li canon and its commentaries. Taking into consideration the wider socio-religious context and drawing from early brahmanical literature and epigraphical findings, it contrasts these descriptions with the doctrinal account of women's spiritual abilities.</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="588"><subfield code="a">Description based on print version of record.</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="596"><subfield code="a">44</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1="0" ind2="0" tag="630"><subfield code="a">Tipi&#7789;aka</subfield><subfield code="x">Criticism, interpretation, etc.</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2="0" tag="650"><subfield code="a">Women in Buddhism.</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2="0" tag="830"><subfield code="a">Routledge critical studies in Buddhism.</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1="4" ind2="0" tag="856"><subfield code="3">University of Alberta Access</subfield><subfield code="u">http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?di